               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1371" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1371" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1371" type="surname" value="CARPENTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1371" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>MARTHA CARPENTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of George Carpenter, a smith, and live in High-street, Woolwich. On the 26th of September, between four and five o'clock, I saw the prisoner in the shop, putting a looking-glass into a bag—I went into the shop, and he asked if I wanted any matches—I perceived the back of the glass on the floor—I said, "Give me my glass out of your bag"—he said, "I have not got it"—I said, "I will charge the constable with you; hand it over to me directly"—he said, "You are a pretty person to charge the constable with me," and gave it to me, and walked out—I told Chittenden, who pursued and took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1372" type="witnessName">
